    <section class="section">
      <h2>Settlement Services</h2>
      <p class="section-intro">
        The Chinese Association of Mississauga helps new immigrants and seniors with important documents and settlement services. Our staff can assist you every step of the way through one-on-one or group consultations.
      </p>

      <!-- PR Card Renewal Section -->
      <div class="main-service-section">
        <h3>PR Card Renewal (æ«å¶å¡æ›´æ–°)</h3>
        
        <p>A PR card is your proof of permanent residency in Canada. You need to renew it when it expires. We can help you with this process.</p>
        
        <div class="important-notice">
          <p>âš ï¸ Important: You must apply online. We can help you with this.</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="step-list">
          <div class="step-item" data-step="1">
            <h3>Who Can Apply?</h3>
            <p>You can renew your PR card if:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Your current PR card has expired OR will expire in the next 9 months</li>
              <li>Your card is lost, damaged, or your name has changed</li>
              <li>You have lived in Canada for at least 2 years (730 days) in the last 5 years</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          
          <div class="step-item" data-step="2">
            <h3>Required Documents</h3>
            <p>Prepare these items before you apply:</p>
            
            <div class="document-list-section">
              <h5>Mandatory Documents</h5>
              <ul class="document-list">
                <li>Current PR Card</li>
                <li>Landing paper</li>
                <li>Passport or travel document valid within 5 years</li>
                <li>Photocopy of all pages of the passport valid within 5 years</li>
                <li>Social Insurance Number (SIN)</li>
                <li>Two photos taken within 1 year (size 50mm x 70mm)</li>
                <li>Address records in Canada and other countries within 5 years</li>
                <li>Education records within 5 years (date, school name, city, province)</li>
                <li>Employment records within 5 years (date, company name, city, province)</li>
                <li>For underage applicants (under 18): birth certificate, school attendance record and transcript</li>
                <li>All legal documents if official name was changed</li>
                <li>Record of leaving and returning to Canada within 5 years (includes city and country while outside Canada)</li>
                <li>If you left Canada for over 1095 days but stayed with a Canadian citizen spouse: spouse's Citizenship certificate, marriage certificate, and employment information</li>
                <li>Application fee: CAD $50</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
          
          <div class="step-item" data-step="3">
            <h3>How to Apply (5 Simple Steps)</h3>
            <ol style="padding-left:24px;line-height:1.8">
              <li>Get all your documents ready (see Step 2)</li>
              <li>Create an account on the Government of Canada's Permanent Residence Portal</li>
              <li>Fill out the online form (we can help you with this)</li>
              <li>Upload your documents and pay the $50 fee online</li>
              <li>Submit your application and keep the confirmation number</li>
            </ol>
            
            <div class="important-notice">
              <p>You cannot send a paper application by mail. It must be done online.</p>
            </div>
            
            <p>All information can be found on the IRCC website under: 
              <br><strong>"Immigration and citizenship" â†’ "New immigrants" â†’ "Get a permanent resident card" â†’ "Apply for, renew or replace a PR card"</strong>
            </p>
            <p>If you find any mistakes here, please refer to the IRCC website for accurate information.</p>
          </div>
          
          <div class="step-item" data-step="4">
            <h3>After You Apply</h3>
            <p>Once you submit your application:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>You will get a confirmation number to check your status online</li>
              <li>Processing takes several weeks (check current times on government website)</li>
              <li>Your new card will be mailed to your Canadian address</li>
              <li>Do not travel outside Canada while waiting for your new card</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          
          <div class="step-item" data-step="5">
            <h3>Traveling While Waiting?</h3>
            <p>If you must travel outside Canada before getting your new PR card:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>You need to apply for a PR Travel Document (PRTD)</li>
              <li>Apply at a Canadian embassy, high commission, or consulate</li>
              <li>This takes 4-6 weeks and costs extra money</li>
            </ul>
            <p>We recommend waiting until you receive your new PR card before traveling.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- å±…ä½è¦æ±‚éƒ¨åˆ† -->
        <div class="residency-requirements">
          <h3>Residency Requirements</h3>
          
          <div class="residency-item">
            <h4>How Long Must I Live in Canada?</h4>
            <p>To keep your permanent resident status, you must live in Canada for at least 730 days (2 years) during the past 5 years. This includes days before you became a permanent resident.</p>
          </div>
          
          <div class="residency-item">
            <h4>What Counts as Living in Canada?</h4>
            <p>Days you are physically in Canada count toward your 730-day requirement. Time spent outside Canada may count if:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>You are accompanying a Canadian citizen spouse or partner</li>
              <li>You are working for a Canadian company outside Canada</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          
          <div class="residency-item">
            <h4>Special Situations</h4>
            <p>If you haven't lived in Canada for 2 years, you may still qualify if you have special reasons, such as:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Serious health problems</li>
              <li>Family emergencies</li>
              <li>Other exceptional circumstances</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Citizenship Application Section -->
      <div class="main-service-section">
        <h3>Citizenship Application (å…¥ç±ç”³è¯·)</h3>
        
        <p>We provide assistance with Canadian citizenship applications, helping you navigate the process from document preparation to submission.</p>
        
        <div class="step-list">
          <div class="step-item" data-step="1">
            <h3>Eligibility Requirements</h3>
            <p>To apply for Canadian citizenship, you must:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Be a permanent resident of Canada</li>
              <li>Have lived in Canada for at least 1,095 days out of the past 5 years</li>
              <li>Have filed your taxes (if required) for at least 3 years out of the past 5</li>
              <li>Be able to speak and understand English or French</li>
              <li>Pass a citizenship test (for applicants aged 18-54)</li>
              <li>Not have any prohibitions (criminal convictions, etc.)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          
          <div class="step-item" data-step="2">
            <h3>Required Documents</h3>
            <p>Prepare these items before you apply:</p>
            
            <div class="document-list-section">
              <h5>Mandatory Documents</h5>
              <ul class="document-list">
                <li>Landing Paper & PR Card</li>
                <li>Two pieces of government ID (such as SIN card, OHIP card, Driver's Licence, etc.)</li>
                <li>Passport valid within 5 years (color photocopy required for commissioner certified true copy)</li>
                <li>Previous citizenship applied date (if applicable)</li>
                <li>Residential address within 5 years (date, address)</li>
                <li>Record of leaving & returning to Canada within 5 years (date, country/city, reason for leaving)</li>
                <li>Record of employment OR/AND education within 5 years (documents required, such as letter of employment, school transcript)</li>
                <li>For child applications: Birth Certificate, and date of parents' Canadian citizenship if applicable</li>
                <li>Two photos for citizenship application</li>
                <li>English language ability proof for applicants aged 18 â€“ 54 (such as LINC LV 4 and up certificate, CELPIP test certificate, transcript of local high school/university)</li>
                <li>Any 3 years' Notice of Assessment within 5 years (all 5 years recommended)</li>
                <li>If you stayed in one country over 183 days within last 4 years: local criminal check record</li>
                <li>Application fee: adult â€“ CAD $630, child (under 18) â€“ CAD $100</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
          
          <div class="step-item" data-step="3">
            <h3>Application Process</h3>
            <ol style="padding-left:24px;line-height:1.8">
              <li>Gather all required documents (see Step 2)</li>
              <li>Complete the application form (we can assist with this)</li>
              <li>Pay the application fee</li>
              <li>Submit your application online or by mail</li>
              <li>Take the citizenship test (if between 18-54 years old)</li>
              <li>Attend a citizenship ceremony</li>
            </ol>
            
            <p>All information can be found on the IRCC website under: 
              <br><strong>"Immigration and citizenship" â†’ "Citizenship" â†’ "Apply for citizenship"</strong>
            </p>
            <p>If you find any mistakes here, please refer to the IRCC website for accurate information.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Other Services -->
      <div class="main-service-section">
        <h3>Other Settlement Services</h3>
        
        <div class="services-list">
          <div class="service-item">
            <h4>In-Home Visit Service <span>ä¸Šé—¨æœåŠ¡</span></h4>
            <div>
              <p>If you are not able to come to the office due to transportation, handicap, or other issues, CAM is now providing in-home visit service.</p>
              <p>Please contact our office first, we will determine if you need in-home visit service, and arrange an appointment for our social worker to visit you.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          
